content:
Intermolecular Forces: Keep molecules together (Solid > Liquid > Gas); 
Thermal Energy: Kinetic energy that keeps molecules apart (Gas > Liquid > Solid); 
State of matter is decided by the competition between these two.

Boyle's Law: $P \propto 1/V$ (at constant $n, T$); 
Charles' Law: $V \propto T$ (at constant $n, P$); 
Gay-Lussac's Law: $P \propto T$ (at constant $n, V$); 
Avogadro's Law: $V \propto n$ (at constant $P, T$).

Ideal Gas Equation: $PV = nRT$; 
$R$ (Universal Gas Constant): $0.0821 \text{ L atm K}^{-1} \text{ mol}^{-1}$, $8.314 \text{ J K}^{-1} \text{ mol}^{-1}$, $2 \text{ cal K}^{-1} \text{ mol}^{-1}$; 
Combined Gas Law: $\frac{P_1V_1}{T_1} = \frac{P_2V_2}{T_2}$.

Dalton's Law: $P_{\text{total}} = P_1 + P_2 + P_3 + \dots$ (for non-reacting gases); 
Partial Pressure ($P_i$) = $X_i \times P_{\text{total}}$ (where $X_i$ is mole fraction); 
$P_{\text{dry gas}} = P_{\text{total}} - \text{Aqueous Tension}$.

Gases consist of tiny particles in random motion; 
Volume of molecules is negligible compared to container; 
No intermolecular forces (for ideal gas); 
Average K.E. $\propto$ Absolute Temperature ($T$).

Graham's Law: $r \propto \frac{1}{\sqrt{M}}$ or $r \propto \frac{1}{\sqrt{d}}$ (constant $P, T$); 
$\frac{r_1}{r_2} = \sqrt{\frac{M_2}{M_1}} = \sqrt{\frac{d_2}{d_1}}$; 
Rate of diffusion ($r$) = $\frac{\text{Volume}}{\text{Time}}$ or $\frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}}$.

Compressibility Factor $Z = \frac{PV}{nRT}$; 
For ideal gas: $Z = 1$ at all $P, T$; 
$Z > 1$: Repulsive forces dominate (hard to compress); 
$Z < 1$: Attractive forces dominate (easy to compress).

Pressure Correction: $(P + \frac{an^2}{V^2})$; 
Volume Correction: $(V - nb)$; 
Van der Waals Equation: $(P + \frac{an^2}{V^2})(V - nb) = nRT$; 
$a$ measures attraction; $b$ measures excluded volume.

Critical Temp ($T_c$): Max temp for liquefaction; 
Critical Pressure ($P_c$): Pressure at $T_c$; 
$T_c = \frac{8a}{27Rb}$, $P_c = \frac{a}{27b^2}$, $V_c = 3b$.
